<HTML>
<head><title>For The Record -- NR</title></head>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>For The Record</H2></CENTER>
<HR>
11-September-1995

<P>

<P>
<LI>Big winners from <B>Ross Perot</B> confab are an ideological grab-bag:
<B>Pat Buchanan, Jesse Jackson, John Kasich</B>. Former Perot pollster
<B>Frank Luntz</B>, however, points out that audience at United We Stand
America convention was not representative of Perot's '92 supporters.
(Would most Americans pay to hear more than three dozen politicians
speak?) . . . GOP presidential candidates addressed group despite
<B>Bill Bennett's</B> warnings not to kowtow to Perot. Not kowtowing
was front-runner <B>Bob Dole</B>, whose speech defended politicians and
criticized isolationism. According to <I>Washington Times</I>, Buchanan
``electrified'' crowd with America First and protectionist messages;
but <B>Alan Keyes</B> slammed Buchanan for downplaying anti-abortion
stand, less popular among UWSA members. <B>Phil Gramm</B> reiterated
pledges to balance budget in first term and to abolish federal
quotas by executive order in first day on job. (Dole recently
told columnist <I>Lally Weymouth</I> he would not issue such executive
orders.) <I>Lamar Alexander</I> predicted that independent candidacy
would re-elect <I>Bill Clinton</I> if party nominates Beltway insider
. . . Also sounding anti-Beltway note was <I>Pete Wilson</I>. Though
moderate/liberal on social issues, Wilson called rising illegitimacy
``the greatest threat I can think of to America's future.'' .
. . Survey for U.S. News finds that whites like <I>Colin Powell</I> more
than blacks do, ``largely because a surprising number of blacks
don't know much about him.'' Of blacks who can identify Powell,
19 per cent don't know his race.
<P>
<LI>Announcement by N.J. Sen.<B> Bill Bradley</B> that he won't run for re-election
next year reduces Democrats' already-slim chances of retaking
Senate. Dems currently hold 6 of 7 Senate seats that will be open
in 1996 -- and they lost all 6 of their open seats in '94. <B>Claiborne
Pell </B>(D., R.I.) is probably next out the door. Will <B>Sam Nunn</B>,
in Republican-friendly Georgia, be far behind? Dems may be lucky
to hold onto the power to filibuster. . . . Race to replace Bradley
is already crowded: among Republicans, Rep. <B>Dick Zimmer</B> is widely
expected to win nomination but <B>Richard DuHaime</B> is challenging
him from the Right; ex-Gov. <B>Tom Kean</B> and Rep. <B>Marge Roukema</B> could
jump in. Main contenders on Democrat side are likely to be Reps.
<B>Robert Torricelli</B> and <B>Robert Andrews</B>, but ex-Gov. <B>Jim Florio</B> is
interested. . . . <B>Newt Gingrich</B> and <B>John Lewis</B> (D., Ga.) -- the
same Lewis who recently disrupted a Gingrich symposium on Medicare
-- joined forces to submit a redistricting proposal to protect
Georgia's 11 congressional incumbents.
<P>
<LI><B>Norma McCorvey</B>, better known as Jane Roe of Roe v. Wade, departed
the pro-choice movement. Feminists,  she complains, never treated
her -- a reform-school dropout, former drug dealer and alcoholic
-- with respect. Reaction from <B>Sarah Weddington</B>, her lawyer in
Roe: ``It doesn't really matter. The case was a class-action suit.''
New York Times piles on: McCorvey ``never was much of a poster
girl for choice,'' declares editorial page. . . . Pro-lifers make
progress in state legislatures across the country. <B>Clarke Forsythe</B>
of Americans United for Life reports in Wall Street Journal that
so far this year four states have passed laws requiring parental
consent or at least notification before a minor daughter's abortion,
leaving only 12 states without such laws. Three states passed
informed-consent laws -- and Missouri would have joined them but
for Dem. Gov. <B>Mel Carnahan's</B> veto. And the Ohio legislature sent
a ban on ``partial-birth'' abortions to GOP Gov. <B>George Voinovich</B>
for his signature.
<P>
<LI>Defection of Lt.-Gen. <B>Hussein Kamel Hassan</B>, head of Iraq's military
industrialization -- including nuclear and poison-gas projects
-- means regime of <B>Saddam Hussein</B> is collapsing. Iraq itself might
splinter, with neighboring states wrangling for pieces in Yugoslav-type
ethnic free-for-all. . . . Colombia Prosecutor-General <B>Alfonso
Valdivieso</B> expects other drug traffickers to replace captured
Cali cartel leaders <B>Miguel Rodriguez Orejuelo</B> and his brother.
Defense Minister <B>Fernando Botero</B> resigned after accusations he
took drug money while running Pres. <B>Ernesto Samper's</B> campaign.
. . . Meanwhile, U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency chief <B>Thomas Constantine</B>
says amphetamines from Mexico are rapidly overtaking Colombian
cocaine as drug of choice in U.S. . . . Mexican police have grabbed
<B>Aaron Morel Lebaron</B>, leader of Texas polygamist sect who is accused
of ordering the murder of three members. . . . Senators <B>John McCain</B>
and <B>Joseph Lieberman</B> are co-sponsoring proposal to establish international
fund to arm Bosnian government. <B>Jesse Helms</B>, chairman of Foreign
Relations Committee, says, ``It's time we treated the Bosnian
people the same way we treated the Contras in Nicaragua and those
people in Afghanistan -- as freedom fighters.'' . . . Russian
ultranationalist <B>Vladimir Zhirinovsky</B> has ordered all his party's
candidates in December parliamentary elections to be examined
for drug addiction, mental illness, and criminal backgrounds.
. . . <B>Vitaly Usov</B>, general manager of new Moscow restaurant offering
traditional Russian fast-food, has taught waitresses to smile
like McDonald's employees.
<P>
<LI><B>Bob Dole</B> voted in Iowa's straw poll, but the <B>Gramms</B> did not. Quips
<B>Charlie Black</B>, Gramm campaign chairman, on the candidates' photo
finish: ``If Wendy hadn't choked on us, we'd have won the thing.''
</BODY>

